[0.927, "o", "\u001b[?2026h\u001b[2D\u001b[4B\r\u001b[2C\u001b[6A\u001b[1mSupersede creates a lineage edge, not a replacement.\u001b[1C\u001b[22mThe\u001b[1Cgraph\u001b[1Cnow\u001b[1Chas\u001b[1C\u001b[38;2;177;185;249minbound-webhooks\u001b[1C\u001b[39m→\u001b[1C\u001b[38;2;177;185;249mSUPERSEDED_BY\u001b[1C\u001b[39m→\r\u001b[1B  \u001b[38;2;177;185;249mevent-ingestion-pipeline\u001b[39m. This means you can trace the architectural evolution: why raw HTTP handlers were \r\u001b[1B  replaced,\u001b[1Cwhat\u001b[1Cdecisions\u001b[1Cwere\u001b[1Cpreserved\u001b[1C(two-layer\u001b[1Cdedup,\u001b[1Cadapter\u001b[1Cpattern),\u001b[1Cand\u001b[1Cwhat\u001b[1Cchanged\u001b[1C(CloudEvents,\r\u001b[1B  schema validation, dead-letter). The superseded spec's full shape/specify/decompose history remains        \r\u001b[2C\u001b[1Bqueryable — nothing is deleted.                          \u001b[1C                                               \r\u001b[2C\u001b[1B                                         \r\r\n\u001b[38;2;136;136;136m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────"]
